  "datePublished": "2026-03-06",
  "description": "Free indirect discourse is a narrative technique that blends the narrator\u0026rsquo;s voice with the character\u0026rsquo;s thought, presenting the character\u0026rsquo;s inner experience in the third person without quotation marks or reporting verbs. It is the sentence that sounds like the character but is grammatically the narrator\u0026rsquo;s.\nConsider three ways to present a character\u0026rsquo;s thought:\nDirect thought: She thought, \u0026ldquo;This party is unbearable.\u0026rdquo; Indirect thought: She thought that the party was unbearable. Free indirect discourse: The party was unbearable. In the third version, the narrator has disappeared into the character\u0026rsquo;s perception. The reader hears the character\u0026rsquo;s judgment (\u0026ldquo;unbearable\u0026rdquo;) in the narrator\u0026rsquo;s grammar (third person, past tense). This creates a double voice — the character\u0026rsquo;s subjectivity carried in the narrator\u0026rsquo;s syntax — that is one of fiction\u0026rsquo;s most powerful and distinctive effects.\n",
